{"title_page": "Miss X (character)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Miss X (disambiguation){{!}}Miss X}}\n{{Superherobox <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| image =\n| caption =\n| character_name = Miss X\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| debut = ''Action Comics'' #26 (May 1940)\n| creators = [[Ken Fitch]] (script)<br>[[Bernard Baily]] (art)\n| alter_ego = Margaret Janice \"Peggy\" Maloney\n| full_name =\n| species = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases = <!-- optional: actual identities the character uses, not nicknames -->\n| supports=<!--optional-->\n| powers = None\n}}\n'''Miss X''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]], [[comic-book]] character in the [[DC Comics]] [[DC Universe|universe]].  She [[first appeared]] in ''[[Action Comics]]'' #26 (May [[1940s in comics|1940]]), in the feature \"[[Tex Thomson]]\".  Although her [[secret identity]] was never expressly revealed, the reader was led to believe it was Margaret Janice Peggy Maloney, the daughter of District Attorney Maloney.\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nMiss X aided [[Tex Thompson]] and Bob Daley after the third member of their team, Gargantua T. Potts, left to become a cook in the French Army. She wore no costume, and her sole disguise consisted of a pair of dark sunglasses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020  |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/miss-x.htm |title=Miss X}}</ref> Tex was intrigued and obsessed with finding out who the mysterious Miss X was.  In the final panel of ''Action Comics'' #29, he confided to his partner that he thought he had figured out who she was.\n\nIn ''Action Comics'' #33, Thompson was declared dead. This turned out to be a ruse, and Thompson returned as [[Mister America (DC Comics)|Mister America]]. Miss X made her final appearance in ''Action Comics'' #43 (Dec. 1941).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/miss-x.htm Miss X] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6frl7dQnT Archived] from the original on march 8, 2016.\n\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miss X (Comics)}}\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1940]]\n[[Category:DC Comics female superheroes]]\n[[Category:DC Comics superheroes]]\n\n\n{{DC-char-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Superherobox <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| image =\n| caption =\n| character_name = Miss X\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| debut = ''Action Comics'' #26 (May 1940)\n| creators = [[Ken Fitch]] (script)<br>[[Bernard Baily]] (art)\n| alter_ego = Margaret Janice \"Peggy\" Maloney\n| full_name =\n| species = <!-- optional -->\n| homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n| alliances = <!-- optional -->\n| aliases = <!-- optional: actual identities the character uses, not nicknames -->\n| supports=<!--optional-->\n| powers = None\n}}\n{{Other uses|Miss X (disambiguation){{!}}Miss X}}\n'''Miss X''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]], [[comic-book]] character in the [[DC Comics]] [[DC Universe|universe]].  She [[first appeared]] in ''[[Action Comics]]'' #26 (May [[1940s in comics|1940]]), in the feature \"[[Tex Thomson]]\".  Although her [[secret identity]] was never expressly revealed, the reader was led to believe it was Margaret Janice Peggy Maloney, the daughter of District Attorney Maloney.\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nMiss X aided [[Tex Thompson]] and Bob Daley after the third member of their team, Gargantua T. Potts, left to become a cook in the French Army. She wore no costume, and her sole disguise consisted of a pair of dark sunglasses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020  |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/miss-x.htm |title=Miss X}}</ref> Tex was intrigued and obsessed with finding out who the mysterious Miss X was.  In the final panel of ''Action Comics'' #29, he confided to his partner that he thought he had figured out who she was.\n\nIn ''Action Comics'' #33, Thompson was declared dead. This turned out to be a ruse, and Thompson returned as [[Mister America (DC Comics)|Mister America]]. Miss X made her final appearance in ''Action Comics'' #43 (Dec. 1941).\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/miss-x.htm Miss X] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6frl7dQnT Archived] from the original on march 8, 2016.\n\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miss X (Comics)}}\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1940]]\n[[Category:DC Comics female superheroes]]\n[[Category:DC Comics superheroes]]\n\n\n{{DC-char-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miss_X_(character)"}
